commentText: I'm in Finland, and lost my job after 20 years. As I had been with my employer for that long, I had 6 months notice period with full pay. And they said that I could come to work if I wanted to, but there was no expectation for me to work during that period. They also paid for me to receive some job-related certifications during that time. So I basically had 6 months of paid vacation. Oh, and as I had unspent vacation-days, they paid those out in cash as well.

commentText: Except in cases of serious or gross misconduct, where an employee can be dismissed immediately without notice, a company in France can terminate an employee and waive the notice period while still paying the corresponding compensation. This is solely the employer's decision, and the employee cannot object. However, if the employee requests to skip the notice period, the employer can refuse and is not required to pay the compensatory indemnity.

commentText: In my company (I live in the Netherlands),  full-time employees get 6 months notice period with full pay. Then a severance pay based on how long they have worked here (usualy 1 month salary for each year), cash for unused holidays, a training budget to upskill themselves in that 6 months, help from HR to look for new jobs, and a legal consultation budget. And each lay-offs must go through works councils (Ondernemingsraad) approval process.

commentText: I worked for a large international company with several offices focused on each major region our customers resided.  One of those offices for EU was in France. During my tenure of a decade with the company we had 3 major layoffs across the company.  1000â€™s were let go.  For all 3, not a single employee from the French office was fired. Not a single one as part of the layoffs.  They kept there jobs and titles for years after others had been thrown to the curb.  After I left, it did finally bite them. The entire office was closed and all of them let go. Every single one of them, but too my understanding all of them were paid over a years worth of severance.  Those in the layoffs before were lucky to get 3 months.    My guess, the company probably also got sued and had to pay even more severance for some of those employees in France.   Funny, how they canâ€™t afford to pay any more severance for those let go in other countries, but can afford to give a good severance to those laid off in France.

commentText: I'm from Czechia, it's the same as France here (or at least very similar). Honestly, great system that benefits both parties. You can't quit immediately either, so the employer has time to hire someone new. And obviously, if both parties agree, you can leave whenever y'all agree to - I've seen a few people that got to compromise on a month instead of two. Can't imagine what it's like, coming into work, not knowing whether I actually still work there.

videoTitle: Getting fired France vs US #usa #american #france #french #cultureshock #corporate #funny
commentText: The thing is "at will employment" is not what employers think it is. You still need a valid reason, that'll hold up in the courts. You could still get sued. Especially past 90 period of employment. Also if an employer ever mentions verbally to you beyond the policy handbook that they are an "at will employer" to you as an excuse to fire you, also can be sued in return. Oh, and the employer can be charged by the state or locality as well.

That is where Indian youths who have been pampered at home fail abroad with social adjustment in a new society. They are home sick all the time. They should be concentrating on learning new language, new culture, new skills, seeing new places, experiencing the diversity and nature and even enjoying the quietness and lonliness filled with personal advancement. Glad that you pointed out many of these things here. Europe or any where else is definitely not a bed of roses. Nobody is waiting for you with open arms to give you a job, a home or a car. It is a healthy struggle here all the way minus nepotism, corruption, unequality and injustice which you are hopefully trying to get away from.

videoTitle: how weâ€™re *actually* getting jobs in 2025 #jobsearch
commentText: You may get bites from very small firms. For larger firms, this is worse than contacting recruiter directly. Interviewing screening and such are usually side things for hiring managers and are more focused on their primary senior job duties. They will more than likely get annoyed and ignore it completely. Especially these days where applicant to role ratios are wack. Chances are they already have dozens of folks contacting them directly.  Networking helps a lot: job fairs, friends, family, hobby groups. Have multiple people look over your resume. Practice interviewing. Other than that it's a number game.

commentText: Everyone who is saying usa is not easiest to get into and has discrimination should know some things. Even in australia you won't get any specialisation of your choice even if you clear both amc exams , the specialities you get are only the seats leftover after all Aussie graduates are taken (doctors are less in australia but so are colleges that produce them)  - and there are few specialities like emergency medicine left for imgs. Not to mention the job scarcity even after clearing plab 1 and plab 2 due to inflation. The salary in nhs is barely liveable in uk , laymen get paid more than doctors in uk. So yes usa has the least discrimination against foreign doctors and the only hurdle is usmle atleast they guarantee a job in specialities like internal medicine , family medicine and emergency medicine if you perform well in usmle and play your cards right from the start.
